{{Galaxy cluster | name = [[Abell catalogue|Abell]] 1835 | image = Abell 1835 Hubble.jpg | caption = Abell 1835 by [[Hubble Space Telescope]], 3.18&prime; view | credit = [[NASA]]/[[STScI]]/[[WikiSky]] | constellation = [[Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]] | epoch = [[Epoch (astronomy)#Julian years and J2000|J2000]] | ra={{RA|14|01}}<ref name="NED">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for Abell 1835 | url=http://ned.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?objname=ABELL+1835&img_stamp=yes&extend=no&hconst=70.5&omegam=0.27&omegav=0.73&corr_z=1 | accessdate=2006-11-28}}</ref> | dec={{DEC|+02|51}}<ref name="NED" /> | member_no = | richness = 0<ref name="ACO">{{cite journal | last1 = Abell | first1 = George O. | authorlink1 = George O. Abell | last2 = Corwin | first2 = Harold G., Jr. | authorlink2 = Harold G. Corwin | last3 = Olowin | first3 = Ronald P. | authorlink3 = Ronald P. Olowin |date=May 1989 | title = A catalog of rich clusters of galaxies | journal = Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series | volume = 70 | issue = May 1989 | pages = 1–138 | format = PDF | issn = 0067-0049 | bibcode = 1989ApJS...70....1A | doi = 10.1086/191333 | accessdate = March 12, 2012 | url = http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?bibcode=1989ApJS...70....1A&page_ind=0&epage_ind=137&type=PRINTER&data_type=PDF_HIGH&email=&emailsize=500&emailsplit=YES&send=GET&verified=YES }}</ref> | redshift = 0.25320<ref name="NED" /> | distance = {{convert|1023|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} {{hub|0.705}} <ref name="NED" /> | flux = (11.30 ± 7.3%){{e|-11}} [[erg]] s<sup>−1</sup> cm<sup>−2</sup> (0.1—2.4 [[electron volt|keV]])<ref name="NED" /> | brightest_member = | other_names = }} '''Abell 1835''' is a [[galaxy cluster]] in the [[Abell catalogue]]. It is a cluster that also [[gravitational lens]]es more-distant background [[galaxy|galaxies]] to make them visible to astronomers. The cluster has a red shift of around 75,900&nbsp;km/[[second|s]] and spans 12&prime;.<ref name="NED" />
In 2004, one of the galaxies lensed by this cluster was proposed to be the most distant galaxy known, [[Galaxy Abell 1835 IR1916]].
