[[File:Mimetite-35216.jpg|thumb|250px|Mimetite (Var.: Campylite)]]
'''Campylite''' is a variety of the [[lead]] [[arsenate]] [[mineral]] [[mimetite]] which received the name from the [[Greek language|Greek]] 'kampylos'- bent, on account of the barrel-shaped bend of its crystals. It has also been used as an alternate name for [[pyromorphite]].
It occurs in the upper lead deposits through the oxidation of [[galena]] or [[cerussite]]. The main deposits are [[Příbram]] in [[Bohemia]] and [[Dry Gill]], [[Caldbeck Fells]], near [[Wigton]], [[Cumbria]], [[England]].
==References== *[http://www.mindat.org/min-6739.html Mindat with location data] *[http://webmineral.com/data/Pyromorphite.shtml Webmineral pyromorphite page]
==Further reading== * Mick Cooper and Chris Stanley, 1990, ''Minerals of the English Lake District,'' Natural History Museum Publications, London, {{ISBN|0-11-310022-1}}
