{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= [[File:FRNS III (HDR) 01.jpg|300px|FRNS III]] |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country= |Ship flag={{FRA}} |Ship name= ''FNRS III'' |Ship ordered= 1950 |Ship awarded= |Ship builder= |Ship original cost= |Ship laid down= |Ship launched= |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed= 1953 |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned= |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship maiden voyage= |Ship in service=1953 |Ship out of service= |Ship renamed= |Ship reclassified= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship homeport= |Ship identification= |Ship nickname= |Ship fate= Preserved at the [[Toulon]] naval base |Ship status= |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship type=[[Deep-submergence vehicle]] |Ship tonnage= |Ship displacement= |Ship tons burthen= |Ship length= {{convert|6.9|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship beam= {{convert|3.2|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship draft={{convert|6|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship power=1kW electric motor |Ship propulsion= |Ship speed= {{convert|0.5|kn}} |Ship range= |Ship endurance= 24h |Ship test depth= {{convert|4000|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship complement=2 |Ship sensors= |Ship armor= |Ship notes= }} |}
The '''FNRS-3''' or '''FNRS III''' is a [[bathyscaphe]] of the [[French Navy]]. It is currently presevered at [[Toulon]]. She set world depth records, competing against a more refined version of her design, the first [[Bathyscaphe Trieste|bathyscaphe ''Trieste'']]. The French Navy eventually replaced her with the bathyscaphe [[FNRS-4]], in the 1960s.<ref name=Paine-1997>Houghton Mifflin, "Ships of the World", '''Lincoln P. Paine''', ''1997'', pg.188</ref>
After damage to the [[FNRS-2]] during its sea trials in 1948, [[NFWO|FNRS]] ran out of funding, and the submersible was sold to the French Navy, in 1950. She was subsequently substantially rebuilt and improved at Toulon naval base, and renamed FNRS-3.<ref name=Britannica-2010-09-09>Encyclopædia Britannica, 2010 Online, 9 September 2010 (accessed 9 September 2010)</ref> She was relaunched in 1953, under the command of [[Georges Houot]], a French naval officer.<ref>University of Washington Press, "Oceanographic History: The Pacific and Beyond", '''Keith R. Benson, Phillip F. Rehbock, ed.s''', ''1993'', 2002, pp.387</ref>
On 15 February 1954, she made a {{convert|4050|m}} dive 160 miles off [[Dakar, Senegal]] in the Atlantic Ocean, beating Piccard's 1953 record, set by the ''Trieste'', by 900 meters.<ref name=Britannica-2010-09-09/><ref name=Paine-2000/><ref name=Time-1954-03-01>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Deepest Divers |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,819513,00.html |work= [[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |date= 1 March 1954 |accessdate=11 January 2009 }}</ref> (the floor of the Mediterranean off Naples, {{convert|10392|ft|m}})<ref name=Paine-2000/><ref>American Heritage, [http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/1992/1/1992_1_28.shtml "To the Bottom of the Sea"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203173230/http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/it/1992/1/1992_1_28.shtml |date=3 December 2008 }}, '''T. A. Heppenheimer''', ''Summer 1992, Volume 8, Issue 1'' (accessed 9 September 2010)</ref> This record was not exceeded until a workup dive by ''Trieste'' in 1959, working up to the record shattering Challenger Deep dive.<ref name=Paine-1997/><ref name=Paine-2000>Mariner Books, "Ships of Discovery and Exploration", '''Lincoln P. Paine''', ''2000'', p.64</ref>
