| spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | module = {{Infobox scientist |embed = yes | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | fields = quantum computing | workplaces = {{plainlist| * [[University of New South Wales]] * [[Defence Science and Technology Organisation]] }} | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of New South Wales]] | thesis_title = Enhanced Nuclear Magnetism | thesis_url = http://primoa.library.unsw.edu.au/UNSWS:UNSW_ALMA21120677450001731 | thesis_year = 1983 | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = {{plainlist| * [[Walter Boas Medal]] 1998<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aip.org.au/info/?q=content/walter-boas-medal |title=Walter Boas Medal |publisher=Australian Institute of Physics |accessdate=30 June 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101054240/http://www.aip.org.au/info/?q=content%2Fwalter-boas-medal |archivedate=1 January 2016 |df= }}</ref> *Eureka Prize for Leadership in Science (2008)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aeri.unsw.edu.au/information-about/people/petroleum/professor-robert-clark-ao |title=Professor Robert Clark AO |publisher=Australian Energy Research Institute, University of New South Wales |accessdate=30 June 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304055953/http://www.aeri.unsw.edu.au/information-about/people/petroleum/professor-robert-clark-ao |archivedate=4 March 2015 |df= }}</ref> }} | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | footnotes = }} }} '''Robert (Bob) Clark''' {{postnominals|country=AUS |AO|FAA|FRSN}} is an Australian [[physicist]]. He was appointed Professor and Chair of Energy Strategy and Policy at [[University of New South Wales]] (UNSW) in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nuclearaustralia.org.au/australias-energy-policy/ |title=Australia's Energy Policy |publisher=Australian Nuclear Association}}</ref><ref name=UNSW>{{cite web |url=https://www.unsw.adfa.edu.au/our-people/leadership/professor-robert-clark-ao-faa-frsn |title=Professor Robert Clark AO FAA FRSN |publisher=University of NSW, Canberra }}</ref> Prior to this he was [[Chief Defence Scientist]] from 2008 to 2011<ref name="Depart">{{cite web |url=http://www.minister.defence.gov.au/2011/08/01/chief-defence-scientist-to-depart-in-october/ |title=Chief Defence Scientist to depart in October |author=Department of Defence Ministers |date=1 August 2011 |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> and Professor of Experimental Physics at University of New South Wales, where he established the National Magnet Laboratory and Semiconductor Nanofabrication Facility.<ref name="RiAUS"/>
Clark joined the [[Royal Australian Navy]] as a Cadet Midshipman in 1969. He graduated from the RAN college with a Bachelor of Science from the [[University of New South Wales]], then served on eight ships before leaving the navy in 1979.<ref name="Depart"/> He holds an MA from Oxford and a PhD from the University of New South Wales.<ref name="RiAUS">{{cite web |url=http://riaus.org.au/people/robert-clark/ |title=Robert Clark |publisher=RiAus - Australia’s Science Channel |date=16 January 2011 |accessdate=30 June 2015 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He took several positions at UNSW, culminating in Director of the Australian Research Council Centre of Excellence for Quantum Computer Technology, before taking on the role of Chief Defence Scientist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.australiandefence.com.au/3AB98840-F807-11DD-8DFE0050568C22C9 |title=Professor Robert Clark takes DSTO reins |date=17 September 2008 |work=Australian Defence Magazine |publisher=Yaffa Media |accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>
Clark was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] on Australia Day 2013 "for distinguished service to science and technology through leadership and governance of the scientific community of the Australian Defence Force and through contributions to quantum computing and nanotechnology".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1146695&search_type=quick&showInd=true |title=Officer of the Order of Australia |work=It's an Honour |publisher=Australian Government |date=26 January 2013 |accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> and was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]] on 1 January 2001 "for contribution to world leading research in the field of quantum computing and physics".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1116964&search_type=simple&showInd=true |title=Centenary Medal |work=It's an Honour |publisher=Australian Government |date=1 January 2001 |accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref> He is a [[Fellow of the Australian Academy of Science]] (2001), a Distinguished Fellow of the [[Royal Society of New South Wales#Distinguished Fellows of the Society|Royal Society of New South Wales]] (2009), and has received numerous other acknowledgements and awards.<ref name=UNSW/>
